Any single man must judge for himself whether circumstances warrant obedience or
resistance to the commands of the civil magistrate; we are all qualified,
entitled, and morally obliged to evaluate the conduct of our rulers. This
political judgment, moreover, is not simply or primarily a right, but like
self-preservation, a duty to God. As such it is a judgment that men cannot part
with according to the God of Nature. It is the first and foremost of our
inalienable rights without which we can preserve no other.

        -- John Locke

